https://prez.dev/description.@value: The point or level from which heights and depths are measured and referenced to for an entity or activity. Typically these are expressed relative to a common global or regional reference datum such as the Australian Height Datum (AHD) or can be related to local reference systems. Specific emphasis is placed on elevation references used by resource exploration and drilling programs, whereby depths are measured relative to local reference datums or specific parts of a borehole/drilling platform. Concepts in this vocabulary include both reference datums (e.g. mean sea level) and how depths are expressed relative to them (e.g. mean sea level height).

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: A tidal low water datum, originally developed by Sir G Darwin for parts of the Indian Ocean. Designed for regions of mixed tides, the datum is depressed below mean sea level by the sum of the amplitudes of the principal semidiurnal lunar and solar tides and the principal diurnal tides (M2 + S2 + K1 + O1). Area of use: World. Users are advised to not use this generic vertical datum but to define explicit realizations of Indian Spring Low Water (ISLW) by specifying location and epoch, for instance 'ISLW at xxx during yyyy-yyyy'.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#hist.@value: Defined in the official EPSG database maintained by OGP Geomatics Committee (http://www.epsg.org/, https://epsg.io/)
